te a branch with the same name as the task branch\n    48→  - Return to the parent directory\n    49→\n    50→Example: If working on tt1-login-ux-flow affecting io_web and io_user_model, create tt1-login-ux-flow branches in both submodules.\n    51→\n    52→**Branch Discipline Rules:**\n    53→- Task frontmatter must list ALL modules that might be edited\n    54→- All listed modules MUST have matching task branches\n    55→- Before editing any file, verify the submodule is on the correct branch\n    56→- If a module needs to be added mid-task, create its branch immediately\n    57→\n    58→> Note: If resuming work on an existing branch:\n    59→> - Check git status first for uncommitted work in super-repo AND all submodules\n    60→>   - Address EVERY file shown in `git status`, not just expected files\n    61→>   - Common missed files: CLAUDE.md, .claude/state files, test outputs\n    62→>   - Either commit ALL changes or explicitly discuss with user\n    63→> - Checkout the branch in the super-repo\n    64→> - For each affected submodule, navigate to it and checkout the matching branch\n    65→> - Only pull from remote if the remote branch exists\n    66→\n    67→## 1. Update Task State\n    68→\n    69→After creating/checking out branches, update the .claude/state/current_task.json file.\n    70→\n    71→**CORRECT FORMAT (use these exact field names):**\n    72→```json\n    73→{\n    74→  \"task\": \"task-name\",        // Just the task name, NO path, NO .md extension\n    75→  \"branch\": \"feature/branch\", // The Git branch name (NOT \"branch_name\")\n    76→  \"services\": [\"service1\"],   // Array of affected services/modules\n    77→  \"updated\": \"2025-08-27\"     // Current date in YYYY-MM-DD format\n    78→}\n    79→```\n    80→\n    81→**COMMON MISTAKES TO AVOID:**\n    82→- ❌ Using `\"task_file\"` instead of `\"task\"`\n    83→- ❌ Using `\"branch_name\"` instead of `\"branch\"`\n    84→- ❌ Including path like `\"tasks/m-task.md\"` instead of just `\"m-task\"`\n    85→- ❌ Including `.md` file extension\n    86→\n    87→## 2. Load Task Context Manifest\n    88→\n    89→Read the Context Manifest section from the task file.\n    90→\n    91→If the Context Manifest is missing:\n    92→- For new tasks: Run context-gathering agent (should have been done during creation)\n    93→- For old tasks: Consider running context-gathering agent to create one\n    94→\n    95→## 3. Load Context & Verify Branch State\n    96→\n    97→Based on the manifest:\n    98→- Read the narrative explanation to understand how everything works\n    99→- Note technical reference details for implementation\n   100→- Check environmental requirements\n   101→- Note file locations for where changes will be made\n   102→- Change the frontmatter status to \"in-progress\"\n   103→- Add \"started: YYYY-MM-DD\" to the front matter\n   104→\n   105→**IF SUPER-REPO: Verify All Module Branches**\n   106→Before starting work, confirm all modules are on correct branches:\n   107→```bash\n   108→# For each submodule in the task\n   109→for module in $(cat .claude/state/current_task.json | jq -r '.services[]'); do\n   110→  cd $module\n   111→  echo \"$module is on branch: $(git branch --show-current)\"\n   112→  cd ..\n   113→done\n   114→```\n   115→\n   116→If any module that will be edited is not on the task branch, STOP and fix it first.\n   117→\n   118→## 4. Verify Understanding\n   119→\n   120→Before diving in:\n   121→- Understand the success criteria\n   122→- Review the work log for previous progress\n   123→- Check for blockers or gotchas\n   124→- Confirm approach with user if needed\n   125→\n   126→## 5. Work Mode\n   127→\n   128→Remember:\n   129→- Follow DAIC protocol (Discussion before Implementation)\n   130→- Use code-review agent after significant changes\n   131→- Update work log as you go\n   132→- Delegate heavy analysis to agents\n   133→\n   134→## Example First Message\n   135→\n   136→\"I've loaded the context for [task]. Based o