   428→        "content": "     1→---\n     2→task: m-implement-transflow-mvp-kb-persistence-layer\n     3→branch: feature/implement-transflow-mvp-kb-persistence-layer\n     4→status: pending\n     5→created: 2025-09-05\n     6→modules: [internal/cli/transflow, internal/storage, internal/orchestration]\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→# Implement Transflow MVP KB Persistence Layer\n    10→\n    11→## Problem/Goal\n    12→Implement the Knowledge Base (KB) persistence layer for the transflow MVP to enable cross-run learning and self-healing optimization. The KB system stores error signatures, healing cases, successful patches, and summary statistics in SeaweedFS with Consul KV coordination to avoid duplication and provide intelligent healing suggestions.\n    13→\n    14→## Success Criteria\n    15→- [ ] KB storage interface with SeaweedFS backend implementation\n    16→- [ ] Consul KV coordination for locks and Compare-And-Swap operations\n    17→- [ ] Error signature normalization and content-addressed storage\n    18→- [ ] Patch fingerprinting and deduplication system\n    19→- [ ] Case storage with sanitized build logs and context\n    20→- [ ] Summary computation with promotion and ranking logic  \n    21→- [ ] Compactor job for maintenance and optimization\n    22→- [ ] Integration with existing transflow self-healing workflow\n    23→- [ ] Unit tests with 60% coverage minimum\n    24→- [ ] Integration tests on VPS deployment infrastructure\n    25→\n    26→## Context Manifest\n    27→\n    28→### How This Currently Works: Transflow Self-Healing Architecture\n    29→\n    30→The transflow system currently implements a comprehensive self-healing workflow through several interconnected components that coordinate recipe execution, build validation, and failure recovery. When a user initiates a transflow run via `ploy transflow run -f transflow.yaml`, the orchestration begins in `internal/cli/transflow/runner.go` which serves as the main coordination point.\n    31→\n    32→The process starts with configuration parsing in `internal/cli/transflow/config.go`, which loads the YAML configuration containing the workflow ID, target repository, transformation steps (typically OpenRewrite recipes), and self-healing settings. The configuration supports a `SelfHealConfig` structure with `MaxRetries`, `Cooldown`, and `Enabled` fields that control the healing behavior. The system validates timeouts, repository URLs, and step definitions during this phase.\n    33→\n    34→Once configured, the runner creates a workflow branch using the naming convention `workflow/<id>/<timestamp>` and begins executing the transformation steps. The primary transformation engine leverages the existing ARF (Automated Refactoring Framework) pipeline through `api/arf/git_operations.go` for Git operations and recipe execution via the OpenRewrite service. Each transformation produces diffs that are committed to the workflow branch.\n    35→\n    36→After transformations complete, the system performs build validation using the existing `internal/cli/common/deploy.go::SharedPush()` function. This creates a tar archive of the transformed code and POSTs it to the controller's `/v1/apps/:app/builds` endpoint. The build system performs comprehensive validation including policy enforcement, vulnerability scanning, and artifact integrity verification. Apps follow the naming convention `tfw-<transflow-id>-<timestamp>` for build isolation.\n    37→\n    38→When builds fail, the self-healing workflow activates through the integration points in `internal/cli/transflow/runner.go:441-500`. The system captures the build error output (stdout/stderr) and initiates a three-phase healing process:\n    39→\n    40→**Phase 1: Planning** - A LangGraph planner job is submitted via the orchestration infrastructure. The planner analyzes the error context, repository metadata, and any existing KB knowledge to generate healing options. These options typically include: human intervention steps, LLM-generated fixes (llm-exec), and OpenRewrite recipe generation (orw-gen). The planner job runs as a containerized Nomad batch job following the contract defined in `roadmap/transflow/jobs/README.md`.\n    41→\n    42→**Phase 2: Fanout Execution** - The `FanoutOrchestrator` in `internal/cli/transflow/fanout_orchestrator.go` executes the healing options in parallel with first-success-wins semantics. Each branch runs as an independent Nomad job, applying its proposed fix and validating the result through build checks. The orchestrator monitors all branches and cancels remaining jobs once the first successful fix is found.\n    43→\n    44→**Phase 3: Reduction** - A reducer job analyzes the branch results and determines next actions. Typically this results in \"stop\" (success) or \"new_plan\" (if additional healing attempts are needed). The reducer also produces metadata for KB persistence.\n    45→\n    46→The current system has interfaces defined in `internal/cli/transflow/types.go` for `JobSubmissionHelper` and `FanoutOrchestrator`, with implementations handling the Nomad job lifecycle through `internal/orchestration/submit.go` and related orchestration utilities.\n    47→\n    48→### Current KB Gap: Missing Persistence and Learning\n    49→\n    50→While the healing workflow is implemented, the KB persistence layer is notably missing. The system currently regenerates healing plans from scratch for each failure, without learning from previous successful fixes or building up institutional knowledge about error patterns. The specification in `roadmap/transflow/kb.md` defines the required persistence architecture, but no implementation exists.\n    51→\n    52→The healing workflow captures rich error information, successful patches, and context metadata, but this data is lost after each run. Without persistent learning, the system cannot:\n    53→- Suggest previously successful fixes for similar error signatures\n    54→- Avoid repeatedly trying failed approaches\n    55→- Improve healing confidence scores over time\n    56→- Provide fast-path fixes for common error patterns\n    57→- Build up domain-specific knowledge for different languages and frameworks\n    58→\n    59→### For New Feature Implementation: KB Persistence Integration Points\n    60→\n    61→The KB persistence layer needs to integrate at several key points in the existing transflow workflow:\n    62→\n    63→**During Planner Job Execution:** The planner job needs read access to KB summaries to suggest previously successful fixes before falling back to LLM generation. The KB read path involves loading `kb/healing/errors/{lang}/{signature}/summary.json` files that contain promoted fixes ranked by success rate, recency, and performance. The planner should check for direct signature matches first, then optionally query vector similarity if available.\n    64→\n    65→**After Branch Completion:** Each successful or failed healing branch needs to write a case record to `kb/healing/errors/{lang}/{signature}/cases/{run_id}.json` containing the complete context: error signature, attempted fix, outcome, build logs (sanitized), and metadata like language, lane, and dependency checksums. This write happens regardless of whether the fix was successful, as failures also provide learning data.\n    66→\n    67→**During Patch Storage:** Successful patches need deduplication through content addressing. The system normalizes unified diffs by removing timestamps and whitespace variations, then computes a SHA-256 fingerprint. Patches are stored once at `kb/healing/patches/{patch_fingerprint}.patch` and referenced by fingerprint from case records.\n    68→\n    69→**Summary Updates:** After writing case data, the system attempts to update the summary statistics under a Consul KV lock. The lock key follows the pattern `kb/locks/{lang}/{signature}` with a short TTL (5s). If lock acquisition fails, the case is written anyway and a periodic compactor job will rebuild summaries later.\n    70→\n    71→**Error Signature Normalization:** The system needs consistent error signature generation by normalizing compiler output - stripping absolute paths, timestamps, and environment-specific details, then hashing the stable error pattern along with language and compiler information. This ensures the same logical error gets the same signature across different environments.\n    72→\n    73→**Sanitization Pipeline:** Before persisting any data, the system must sanitize build logs and user content by masking authentication tokens (GitHub PATs, GitLab tokens, JWTs), stripping absolute paths that might contain usernames, and truncating excessively long logs to prevent storage bloat.\n    74→\n    75→### Storage Architecture Integration\n    76→\n    77→The KB system leverages existing storage infrastructure in the platform:\n    78→\n    79→**SeaweedFS Integration:** The system uses the existing SeaweedFS client in `internal/storage/seaweedfs.go` for blob storage. KB files are stored under a dedicated namespace (`kb/`) with the hierarchical structure defined in the specification. The existing storage interface in `internal/storage/interface.go` provides the necessary `Store()`, `Get()`, `List()`, and `Delete()` operations.\n    80→\n    81→**Consul KV Coordination:** The KB uses the existing Consul KV interface in `internal/orchestration/kv.go` for distributed coordination. This provides atomic Compare-And-Swap operations for summary updates and distributed locking to prevent concurrent writers from corrupting shared state.\n    82→\n    83→**Configuration Integration:** KB configuration extends the existing transflow configuration in `internal/cli/transflow/config.go`. New fields control KB behavior: read/write endpoints, retention policies, compaction schedules, and feature flags for gradual rollout.\n    84→\n    85→### Job Templates and Orchestration\n    86→\n    87→The KB system integrates with the existing job orchestration pattern:\n    88→\n    89→**Compactor Job:** A periodic Nomad job template (similar to those in `roadmap/transflow/jobs/`) runs compaction tasks. The compactor scans case files, recomputes summaries with updated statistics, rebuilds vector indices if enabled, and prunes stale or blacklisted data. This job template follows the same orchestration pattern as planner/reducer jobs.\n    90→\n    91→**KB Snapshot Generation:** The compactor produces `kb/healing/snapshot.json` manifests containing timestamp, language counts, statistics, and version information. These manifests enable efficient KB state tracking and validation.\n    92→\n    93→**Template Integration:** The existing job templates in `roadmap/transflow/jobs/` (planner.hcl, reducer.hcl) need modification to mount KB snapshot data as read-only volumes. The orchestration code in `internal/orchestration/render.go` handles template variable substitution for KB paths and configuration.\n    94→\n    95→### Technical Reference Details\n    96→\n    97→#### Component Interfaces & Signatures\n    98→\n    99→New KB interfaces to be implemented:\n   100→\n   101→```go\n   102→// KB Storage Interface\n   103→type KBStorage interface {\n   104→    // Error signature and case operations\n   105→    WriteCase(ctx context.Context, lang, signature, runID string, caseData *CaseRecord) error\n   106→    ReadCases(ctx context.Context, lang, signature string) ([]*CaseRecord, error)\n   107→    \n   108→    // Summary operations with locking\n   109→    ReadSummary(ctx context.Context, lang, signature string) (*SummaryRecord, error)\n   110→    WriteSummary(ctx context.Context, lang, signature string, summary *SummaryRecord) error\n   111→    \n   112→    // Patch deduplication\n   113→    StorePatch(ctx context.Context, fingerprint string, patch []byte) error\n   114→    GetPatch(ctx context.Context, fingerprint string) ([]byte, error)\n   115→    \n   116→    // Snapshot and maintenance\n   117→    WriteSnapshot(ctx context.Context, snapshot *SnapshotManifest) error\n   118→    ReadSnapshot(ctx context.Context) (*SnapshotManifest, error)\n   119→}\n   120→\n   121→// Lock coordination for atomic updates\n   122→type KBLockManager interface {\n   123→    AcquireLock(ctx context.Context, key string, ttl time.Duration) (*Lock, error)\n   124→    ReleaseLock(ctx context.Context, lock *Lock) error\n   125→}\n   126→\n   127→// Error signature normalization\n   128→type SignatureGenerator interface {\n   129→    GenerateSignature(lang, compiler string, stdout, stderr []byte) string\n   130→    NormalizePatch(patch []byte) ([]byte, string) // returns normalized patch and fingerprint\n   131→}\n   132→```\n   133→\n   134→Integration with existing interfaces:\n   135→\n   136→```go\n   137→// Extend JobSubmissionHelper (internal/cli/transflow/types.go)\n   138→type JobSubmissionHelper interface {\n   139→    SubmitPlannerJob(ctx context.Context, config *TransflowConfig, buildError string, workspace string) (*PlanResult, error)\n   140→    SubmitReducerJob(ctx context.Context, planID string, results []BranchResult, winner *BranchResult, workspace string) (*NextAction, error)\n   141→    \n   142→    // New KB integration methods\n   143→    LoadKBContext(ctx context.Context, lang, signature string) (*KBContext, error)\n   144→    WriteKBCase(ctx context.Context, caseRecord *CaseRecord) error\n   145→}\n   146→```\n   147→\n   148→#### Data Structures\n   149→\n   150→Key data structures following the schemas:\n   151→\n   152→```go\n   153→type CaseRecord struct {\n   154→    RunID       string                 `json:\"run_id\"`\n   155→    Timestamp   time.Time             `json:\"timestamp\"`\n   156→    Language    string                `json:\"language\"`\n   157→    Signature   string                `json:\"signature\"`\n   158→    Context     *CaseContext          `json:\"context\"`\n   159→    Attempt     *HealingAttempt       `json:\"attempt\"`\n   160→    Outcome     *HealingOutcome       `json:\"outcome\"`\n   161→    BuildLogs   *SanitizedLogs        `json:\"build_logs\"`\n   162→}\n   163→\n   164→type SummaryRecord struct {\n   165→    Language  string         `json:\"language\"`\n   166→    Signature string         `json:\"signature\"`\n   167→    Promoted  []PromotedFix  `json:\"promoted\"`\n   168→    Stats     *SummaryStats  `json:\"stats\"`\n   169→}\n   170→\n   171→type PromotedFix struct {\n   172→    Kind           string    `json:\"kind\"` // \"orw_recipe\" or \"patch_fingerprint\"\n   173→    Ref            string    `json:\"ref\"`\n   174→    Score          float64   `json:\"score\"`\n   175→    Wins           int       `json:\"wins\"`\n   176→    Failures       int       `json:\"failures\"`\n   177→    LastSuccessAt  time.Time `json:\"last_success_at\"`\n   178→}\n   179→```\n   180→\n   181→#### Storage Layout\n   182→\n   183→Following the specification in `roadmap/transflow/kb.md`:\n   184→\n   185→```\n   186→kb/\n   187→├── healing/\n   188→│   ├── errors/\n   189→│   │   └── {lang}/\n   190→│   │       └── {signature}/\n   191→│   │           ├── cases/\n   192→│   │           │   └── {run_id}.json\n   193→│   │           └── summary.json\n   194→│   ├── patches/\n   195→│   │   └── {patch_fingerprint}.patch\n   196→│   ├── blacklist/\n   197→│   │   ├── {signature}.json\n   198→│   │   └── {patch_fingerprint}.json\n   199→│   └── snapshot.json\n   200→└── locks/\n   201→    └── {lang}/\n   202→        └── {signature}  # Consul KV keys\n   203→```\n   204→\n   205→#### Configuration Requirements\n   206→\n   207→Extend `TransflowConfig` in `internal/cli/transflow/config.go`:\n   208→\n   209→```yaml\n   210→version: v1alpha1\n   211→id: workflow-example\n   212→target_repo: https://gitlab.com/org/project.git\n   213→base_ref: refs/heads/main\n   214→\n   215→# Existing fields...\n   216→steps: [...]\n   217→self_heal:\n   218→  enabled: true\n   219→  max_retries: 2\n   220→  \n   221→  # New KB configuration\n   222→  kb:\n   223→    enabled: true\n  